  <section id="title">
    <fragment id="1">
      <heading level="1">Turtles of the Galápagos</heading>
    </fragment>
  </section>
  <section id="content">
    <fragment id="2">
      <heading level="2">
        <bold>Introduction</bold>
      </heading>
      <para>The Galápagos Islands are home to some of the world’s most iconic turtle species, most notably the <bold>
        Galápagos giant tortoise
      </bold> (<italic>Chelonoidis nigra</italic> complex) and several species of <bold>marine turtles</bold>, including
        the <bold>Green sea turtle</bold> (<italic>Chelonia mydas</italic>). These species play crucial ecological roles
        and serve as symbols of conservation efforts across the archipelago.
      </para>
    </fragment>
    <fragment id="3">
      <heading level="2">
        <bold>Key Species</bold>
      </heading>
    </fragment>
    <fragment id="4">
      <heading level="3">
        <bold>Galápagos Giant Tortoise</bold>
      </heading>
      <list>
        <item>Largest living tortoise on Earth</item>
        <item>Can live over 100 years</item>
        <item>Known for distinct shell shapes (domed or saddle-backed)</item>
      </list>
    </fragment>
    <fragment id="5">
      <heading level="3">
        <bold>Green Sea Turtle</bold>
      </heading>
      <list>
        <item>Only sea turtle species that nests in the Galápagos</item>
        <item>Primarily herbivorous</item>
        <item>Migratory, traveling long distances across the Pacific</item>
      </list>
    </fragment>
    <fragment id="6">
      <heading level="2">
        <bold>Ecological Importance</bold>
      </heading>
      <para>Galápagos turtles contribute to ecosystem health by:</para>
      <list>
        <item>Dispersing seeds</item>
        <item>Maintaining vegetation through grazing</item>
        <item>
          <para>Influencing landscape structure through movement patterns</para>
        </item>
      </list>
      <para>Marine turtles help maintain healthy seagrass beds and coral reef systems.</para>
    </fragment>
    <fragment id="7">
      <heading level="2">
        <bold>Threats and Conservation</bold>
      </heading>
    </fragment>
    <fragment id="8">
      <heading level="3">
        <bold>Major Threats</bold>
      </heading>
      <list>
        <item>Habitat loss</item>
        <item>Invasive species (rats, pigs, goats)</item>
        <item>Illegal hunting (historically)</item>
        <item>Plastic pollution and fishing bycatch (for marine turtles)</item>
        <item>Climate change impacting nesting success</item>
      </list>
    </fragment>
    <fragment id="9">
      <heading level="3">
        <bold>Conservation Actions</bold>
      </heading>
      <list>
        <item>Captive breeding and reintroduction</item>
        <item>Predator control and eradication programs</item>
        <item>Nest monitoring and protection</item>
        <item>
          <para>Marine reserves and regulated fishing zones</para>
        </item>
      </list>
    </fragment>
    <fragment id="10">
      <heading level="2">
        <bold>Quick Reference Table</bold>
      </heading>
      <table>
        <col part="header"/>
        <col/>
        <col/>
        <col/>
        <row part="header">
          <cell>Species</cell>
          <cell>Habitat</cell>
          <cell>Status</cell>
          <cell>Notable Traits</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <hcell>Galápagos Giant Tortoise</hcell>
          <cell>Terrestrial, highlands &amp; arid zones</cell>
          <cell>Vulnerable/endangered depending on subspecies</cell>
          <cell>Massive size, long lifespan</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <hcell>Green Sea Turtle</hcell>
          <cell>Coastal waters, beaches</cell>
          <cell>Endangered</cell>
          <cell>Only Galápagos-nesting sea turtle</cell>
        </row>
      </table>
    </fragment>
    <fragment id="11">
      <heading level="2">
        <bold>Notes</bold>
      </heading>
      <list>
        <item>The archipelago once hosted <bold>15 tortoise species</bold>, though several are now extinct.
        </item>
        <item>Some populations have been successfully restored through breeding programs.</item>
        <item>
          <para>Sea turtles in the Galápagos are sometimes seen resting near mangroves and rocky shorelines.</para>
        </item>
      </list>
    </fragment>
    <fragment id="12">
      <block label="warning">
        <para>⚠️
          <bold>Visitors to the Galápagos must not touch or approach turtles.</bold>
        </para>
        <para>Human disturbance can cause nest abandonment, stress, or interference with natural behavior. Maintain
          distance and follow guidelines set by the Galápagos National Park.
        </para>
      </block>
    </fragment>
